{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569860","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569860"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:34:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:34:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22413"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22413","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22413"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.19,0.41,0.06,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15378"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109449"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15378","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15378"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22413"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91814"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2342"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"},{"type":"tags","id":"13199"},{"type":"tags","id":"13200"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"40914"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40915"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40916"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48424"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109449","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109449"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine follow up appointment. Six months ago, she had a coronary calcium score of 156 Agatston units performed due to a family history of early myocardial infarction in her parent at age 48 years. She has no personal history of cardiovascular events. Since her last visit, she has been exercising regularly, trying to follow a Mediterranean diet, and has commenced rosuvastatin and perindopril. She asks about her future risk of stroke.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her blood pressure is now 128/82 mmHg. Recent blood tests show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETotal cholesterol 4.2 mmol/L (3.9-5.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELDL 2.1 mmol/L (2.0-3.4)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHDL 1.4 mmol/L (1.0-2.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETriglycerides 1.5 mmol/L (0.5-1.7).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following factors makes her ineligible for use of the Australian CVD risk calculator?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Age less than 55 years","Family history of early cardiovascular disease","Coronary calcium score \u003E100","Current antihypertensive therapy","Current statin therapy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe Australian CVD risk calculator is specifically designed for primary prevention in people without established cardiovascular disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe coronary calcium score is a CT-based measurement that quantifies the amount of calcium in the coronary arteries, reported in Agatston units. It serves as a direct marker of atherosclerotic burden. Scores of 0 indicate no identifiable disease, 1-99 indicates mild disease, 100-399 indicates moderate disease, and \u0026gt;400 indicates severe disease. A \u003Cstrong\u003Ecoronary calcium score \u0026gt;100 \u003C/strong\u003Erepresents significant atherosclerotic burden and is considered evidence of established cardiovascular disease, warranting aggressive risk factor modification including high dose statin therapy and aspirin regardless of traditional risk calculations. This makes the use of risk calculators inappropriate in this patients case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAge less than 55 years\u003C/strong\u003E is not a contraindication to using the Australian CVD risk calculator, which is validated for use in people aged 45-79 years (or 30-79 years for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples and 35-79 years in individuals with Diabetes).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFamily history of early cardiovascular disease\u003C/strong\u003E is one of the reclassification factors which can be used to refine a patients risk profile following use of the risk calculator and is not a contraindication to its use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECurrent antihypertensive therapy\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Ecurrent statin therapy\u003C/strong\u003E do not preclude use of the calculator, though they should be considered when interpreting results and making management decisions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A coronary calcium score \u003E100 indicates established atherosclerotic cardiovascular disease, making CVD risk calculators inappropriate.","The Australian CVD risk calculator is only valid for primary prevention in people without established cardiovascular disease.","Coronary calcium scoring quantifies arterial calcification as a marker of atherosclerotic burden, with scores \u003E100 indicating moderate to severe disease."],"references":["Australian absolute cardiovascular disease risk calculator. In: National Vascular Disease Prevention Alliance [online]. Accessed 2025 Jun 25. Available at: https://www.cvdcheck.org.au/calculator","Chua A, Blankstein R, Ko B. Coronary artery calcium in primary prevention. Australian Journal of General Practice. 2020;49:464-9. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2020/august/coronary-artery-calcium-in-primary-prevention"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91814"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22413"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91814","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91814"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-21T13:34:08+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-21T13:34:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15378"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109449"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"grou